# Project Architecture and Coding Rules

## Pages
- Keep `pages/` as entry points only.
- Do not place business logic, API calls, or heavy processing in pages.
- Pages should compose and render components.

## Components
- Keep UI and feature logic inside `components/`.
- Components must be reusable, modular, and focused.
- Split large monolithic components into smaller units.
- Prefer this structure:
  - `components/common/` for shared reusable components
  - `components/common/icons/` for all icons
  - `components/<feature>/` for feature-specific components

## State Management (Redux Toolkit)
- Keep Redux state in `app/state/`.
- Use Redux Toolkit for all Redux state handling.
- Create one slice per module in `app/state/slices/`.
- Keep store configuration in `app/state/index.ts`.

## Services (API Layer)
- Place all API calls in `services/`.
- Never call APIs directly from `components/` or `pages/`.
- Keep services clean, reusable, and focused on data access.

## Hooks
- Place custom hooks in `hooks/`.
- Extract reusable component logic into hooks.

## Routing
- Keep routing logic in `routes/`.

## Layouts
- Place layout components (header, sidebar, shell wrappers) in `layouts/`.

## Context
- Place global React contexts in `context/`.

## Guards
- Place route protection logic (auth guards, role guards) in `guards/`.

## Utils
- Keep helper functions, constants, and formatters in `utils/`.

## Additional Best Practices
- Prefer feature-based structure when it improves scalability and clarity.
- Keep files small, readable, and easy to maintain.
- Avoid duplication by reusing components, hooks, services, and utils.
- Maintain consistent naming conventions across the codebase.
- Write for growth: assume features will expand over time.
- Keep clear separation of concerns:
  - UI in components
  - Logic in hooks and services
  - State in Redux slices
